            </form>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>We should acknowledge the real conflicts of interest that exist in an election such as this one, but we should not deny ourselves an opportunity to authentically discuss and engage with the diversity of ideas and perspectives of this university in the name of <a href="http://www.slate.com/articles/life/the_good_word/2010/04/its_time_to_retire_kabuki.html">racialized rhetoric</a> like “<a href="http://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2016/01/yt-candidates-schreiber-and-rooney-decline-to-attend-bsa-endorsement-meetings">totally Kabuki theater</a>” or a supposed “no semblance of impartiality.”</p>
<p>All that we prove by refusing such opportunities is that perhaps we&mdash;and our peers who campaign to serve on the Board of the University&mdash;are as afraid of scary ideas and divisive topics that challenge our beliefs as the pundits would have the world believe.</p>
<p>I have to believe that we and, by extension, our campus politics can be better.</p>
<p><em>Jay Sullivan is a Trinity senior. His column runs on alternate Mondays.</em></p>

